  4) Hardware requirement and How to build PMIP6D
-----------------------------------------
	4.1) HARWARE REQUIREMENT
 
		In our PMIP6D implementation, the Mobile Node's attachment and detachment phases are done at layer 2 using SYSLOG messages exchanged between the Access Point and the MAG.
		WARNING ! : For this reason, you do need to use these CISCO ACCESS POINTs -> Aironet 1100 series. AIR-AP 1120 B SERIES 
		We will soon more test about the compatibility with other kind of APs. 

	4.2) HOW TO BUILD PMIP6D
	
		4.2.1) Installation of the required packages  : 
			libpcap-dev / indent / bison / flex / iproute-dev / macchanger / libc6-dev
			Open a new shell and type :
				$ apt-get install libpcap-dev indent bison flex iproute-dev

		4.2.2) Kernel recompilation
			PMIP6D does not require to modify/patch the kernel, however some features are by default disable and we need to enable them.
			Follow the "INSTALL.kernel" text file to know how to set up correctly your kernel.
		
		4.2.3) Proxy Mobile-IPv6 Daemon compilation
			Follow the "INSTALL" text file to know hot to build PMIP6D tool.
		
		4.2.4) Mobile Nodes network prefixes 
			In this PMIP6D directory, you will find a file called "match". This file makes the link between the MNs MAC Address and the Network prefix they should receive inside the PMIP domain.
			First of all, copy this "match" file to "/etc" path on your system.
				$ cp pmip6d/match /etc/
			Each line of this "match" file is one MOBILE NODE's MAC ADDRESS authorised to connect the PMIP domain.
			So edit this file and customise it according to your settings.
			EXAMPLE:
				You want to authorise a mobile node which has for MAC ADDRESS 123456789ABC and give it the following IPv6 network prefix: 2001::/64. You thus have to add to the "/etc/match" file :  								20010000000000000000000000000001 00000000000000000000123456789ABC

